post_text:
Today is School Lunch Hero Day. A huge thank you to all of our Food Service staff for everything they do each day and for helping ensure our students have access to food during this time. We also want to extend a thank you to our transportation staff and volunteers who have helped with meal kit distribution over the past weeks.

Speaking of meal kits, our next meal kit distribution is scheduled for Monday, May 4. The distribution will take place from 4 p.m. to 6 p.m. in the circle drive on the north side of Howell High School. For families who lack transportation to pick up a meal kit, delivery will be available. To request delivery, please visit http://bit.ly/2vZoHa2. All requests for delivery will need to be submitted by 2 p.m. on Sunday, May 3. mealThis will allow our Food Service and Transportation Departments to plan for the deliveries.

post_text:
On Monday, March 16, Monday, March 23, and Monday, March 30, from 4 to 6 p.m., our Food Service Department will be providing free meal kits to any families who need them. There is no ID or income requirement to receive a meal kit. The kits will contain seven days of breakfast and lunch foods. The meal kits will be available for pick-up from 4 to 6 p.m. in the circle driveway on the north side of Howell High School (near the rock).

For families who are unable to secure transportation to pick up a kit, the district will offer delivery. If you need a kit delivered, please visit https://forms.gle/Y8k9Bke2ccotusjJ9.

post_text:
Howell Gymnastics Makes History as KLAA Champions
Written by: Molly Carney, Photo by: Dan Zeppa

On Feb. 15, Howell Gymnastics made history as they recently won their very first KLAA championship with 140.15 points. Howell was led by Alyssa Murphey, Alyssa Webber, and Audrey Kane. In Division 1, Murphey finished second all-around with a score of 36.0 and took third in the floor exercise and fourth on bars. Weber was fourth all-around, scoring a 35.625 and finished fourth on beam and fifth on vault. In Division 2, Kane took first all-around scoring a 34.9. Congratulations to the Howell Gymnastics team, keep up the good work ladies! ‚Äú This year, our team is working really hard to accomplish our goals and have a great season. We are a very close team, and we bring out the best in one another by cheering each other on at our meets,‚Äù Murphy says.
text:
Howell Gymnastics Makes History as KLAA Champions
Written by: Molly Carney, Photo by: Dan Zeppa

On Feb. 15, Howell Gymnastics made history as they recently won their very first KLAA championship with 140.15 points. Howell was led by Alyssa Murphey, Alyssa Webber, and Audrey Kane. In Division 1, Murphey finished second all-around with a score of 36.0 and took third in the floor exercise and fourth on bars. Weber was fourth all-around, scoring a 35.625 and finished fourth on beam and fifth on vault. In Division 2, Kane took first all-around scoring a 34.9. Congratulations to the Howell Gymnastics team, keep up the good work ladies! ‚Äú This year, our team is working really hard to accomplish our goals and have a great season. We are a very close team, and we bring out the best in one another by cheering each other on at our meets,‚Äù Murphy says.

post_text:
Michigan State Police Trooper Visits Northwest Elementary
Written by: Patrick Mueller, Photos by: Patrick Mueller, Sarah Grangood

On Tues. Feb. 4, Trooper Adams from the Michigan State Police gave a presentation to Mrs. Kleckner‚Äôs 2nd graders about the importance of law enforcement and tips on what to do during dangerous situations. Trooper Adams has been involved in law enforcement for four years and has been speaking to kids throughout his career. In his presentation, Trooper Adams discussed topics that included what to do around strangers, what to do if you have been robbed, and how to behave on a 911 call. Besides the presentation, the 2nd graders also participated in activities such as question and answer period, where students could ask about things like Adams‚Äôs background and his daily routine. The students also had the opportunity to observe his patrol car. ‚ÄúI love my job because it allows me to keep people safe,‚Äù Trooper Adams says.

post_text:
Brooks Gibbs Northwest Elementary
Written by: Patrick Mueller Photos by: Nan Frimodig

On Thursday, Jan. 23, Brooks Gibbs visited Northwest Elementary School to discuss with students the consequences of bullying. Mr. Gibbs has been speaking on the topic of bullying for over 20 years. Since Mr. Gibbs‚Äôs started speaking to kids, he has received thousands of letters and emails from students, teachers, and administrators, telling stories and reflecting on experiences where his presentations have made a difference in their respected schools. Mr. Gibbs encourages everybody to contribute to the stand against bullying and school violence. ‚ÄúMy motto is ‚ÄúHeart your haters,‚Äù Gibbs says.

The Howell High School Interact Club‚Äôs annual Ribbon Warriors fundraiser is currently underway. So far, the Highlanders have raised over $3000 to support Howell Public Schools families affected by cancer. You can donate to Ribbon Warriors at www.fundalife.org/RW2020.

Join us at the Boys Varsity Basketball game on Tuesday, February 11 at 7 p.m. in the HHS Fieldhouse as we wrap up fundraising efforts. Make a donation of $20 or more and receive a limited edition Ribbon Warriors shirt and be entered to win prizes at half time. Ryan Lane, Michael Sutton, and Matthew Armbruster will shave their heads in support of those impacted by the effects of cancer.

Highlights from Ribbon Warriors 2020 include a Spirit Week with the Freshmen earning donations from our sponsors, a staff v. student Volleyball game at the FC, a coin collection called ‚ÄòStop the Clock‚Äô that resulted in over $500 in coins, donut and walking taco sales, a silent auction, t-shirt sales, and more. #RW2020.

post_text: January 9 is National Law Enforcement Appreciation Day. Our district is lucky to have the best school resource officers supporting us and working each day to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Officer Banfield from the City of Howell Michigan Police Department works with our schools and students within the city limits, and Deputy Bill Schuster from the Livingston County MI Sheriff's Office works with our schools outside the city limits. We also need to give a shout-out to the county's incredible attendance and early literacy office Deputy Kim Lockhart. Thank you to Officer Banfield, Deputy Schuster, and Deputy Lockhart for all you do!

Story by: Owen Wood, Photo by: Mrs. Schoendorff

On Thursday, December 5, The Voices of Voyager Choir, performed at the Cleary University Tree Lighting Ceremony. Approximately 80 students attended with their families. "The staff and students and Cleary do an amazing job at providing an enjoyable and entertaining event that the entire family can enjoy, I am honored that my choir is part of it," said Mrs. Schoendorff, Voyager music teacher.

post_text:
Parker Middle School Choir Sings at the Fox Theater,
Written by: Maria Manarino
Pictures by: Kelli Falls

On Friday, Nov. 22. 6th through 8th grade, Parker Choir students were invited to perform on the steps of the grand stairway inside the Fox Theater in Detroit Fox before the show "The Grinch Who Stole Christmas, the Musical." They had more than 340 family members, students and friends attend the event. The students sang songs performed in Parker's Madrigal Dinner and traditional Christmas Carols for the audience. Their performance lasted about 20 minutes. The students were very excited as it was a big honor to perform there. ¬®Hopefully the students will remember the opportunities that are offered to them as middle school singers and how much they are respected as young adults Ãà Parker chorale director Kelli Falls says.

post_text: Congratulations to Howell Public Schools Fire Academy alumna Brittany Tooman on her new position as a full-time firefighter/EMT with the Ann Arbor Fire Department.
shared_text:
Howell Public Schools Fire Academy
September 3, 2019 at 8:11 PM ¬∑

Howell Schools Fire Academy would like to congratulate Brittany Tooman on her new position as a full-time firefighter/EMT with the Ann Arbor Fire Department.
Brittany was a cadet with the Howell Schools Fire Academy back in Academy #3. Since completing that, she has worked part-time with South Lyon Fire Department while earning her Emergency Medical Technician (EMT) certification. Brittany has helped as an instructor at the fire academy since graduation, and we wish her all the best in her new position.
